## IV. The Diagnostician: Bruce Schneier, Book by Book, Warning by Warning

Bruce Schneier is a public-interest technologist working at the intersection of security, technology, and people. He has been writing about security issues on his blog since 2004 and in his monthly newsletter since 1998. He is a fellow and lecturer at Harvard’s Kennedy School, a board member of EFF, and the Chief of Security Architecture at Inrupt, Inc. He is an internationally renowned security technologist and the New York Times bestselling author of 14 books. He has spent twenty years producing the most precise diagnosis of the surveillance state available in the English language. He has watched every one of his warnings validated. None of his proposed solutions have been implemented at federal scale.

### Data and Goliath (2015): The Diagnosis

*Data and Goliath: The Hidden Battles to Collect Your Data and Control Your World* is a book about surveillance, both government and corporate. It is an exploration in three parts: what’s happening, why it matters, and what to do about it. Schneier wrote: “We’ve been on a headlong path of more and more surveillance, fueled by fear — of terrorism mostly — on the government side, and convenience on the corporate side. My goal was to step back and say ‘wait a minute; does any of this make sense?’”

The book’s structure consists of 16 chapters divided over three parts: (1) “The world we’re creating”; (2) “What’s at stake”; and (3) “What to do about it.” Every single section has a lesson, usually concisely expressed in the last sentence — a “take-away sentence” that makes it both inspiring and easier to grasp for laymen as well as professionals.

Schneier’s framework rests on interlocking structural arguments:

**All personal data collection is surveillance.** Schneier refers to all types of personal data collection as “surveillance,” whether the information is gathered for law enforcement or intelligence purposes, acquired for commercial use, or recorded for no particular reason at all. Under this sweeping definition, the National Security Agency and the FBI perform surveillance, but so do Google, Sears, and the local liquor store. Part 1 describes the role of data in a surveillance society. It starts by defining data as a by-product of computing, emphasizing that access to the data surrounding a person means access to that person. Subsequently, it explains how data can be used as surveillance, emphasizing that content data collection is invasive, and metadata equally so.

**De-anonymization destroys the fiction of aggregate data.** Chapter 3 moves to the analysis of data and explains the correlations made possible by Big Data analytics, and how even large sets of anonymous data can presently be de-anonymized. It concludes by stating that more robust techniques for preserving anonymity are needed.

**The business of surveillance.** The business of surveillance is discussed in Chapter 4, which focuses on corporate surveillance and the exchange of our data for services. It explains Internet tracking via cookies, behavioral advertising as well as the data broking industry. While doing so, it studies power concentrations in this industry and loss of control of users over their computer environment.

**Government surveillance.** Chapter 5 turns to government surveillance, with a focus on the US agencies and the Snowden revelations, while also looking at other governments’ practices, including the UK and Germany.

**Corporate and government surveillance are symbiotic, not separate.** A very important point made in Chapter 6 is that corporate surveillance and government surveillance are intertwined, supporting one another. The data flows bidirectionally. Google and other firms that collect massive amounts of private data from their customers have set up a situation in which the privacy rights of millions, even billions, depend solely on the good intentions of a few powerful decision-makers in private companies.

**The real binary is liberty versus control.** Schneier reframes the fundamental debate: “The real choice is liberty versus control. Tyranny, whether it arises under threat of foreign physical attack or under constant domestic authoritative scrutiny, is still tyranny. Liberty requires security without intrusion, security plus privacy. Widespread police surveillance is the very definition of a police state. And that’s why we should champion privacy even when we have nothing to hide.”

**Privacy is not about hiding wrongdoing.** The most common retort against privacy advocates — by those in favor of ID checks, cameras, databases, data mining and other wholesale surveillance measures — is: “If you aren’t doing anything wrong, what do you have to hide?” Schneier’s response: “My problem with quips like these — as right as they are — is that they accept the premise that privacy is about hiding a wrong. It’s not. Privacy is an inherent human right, and a requirement for maintaining the human condition with dignity and respect.”

**The chilling effect is the mechanism of control.** Schneier identifies threats to political liberty and justice: governments could potentially squash political dissent and social change, put in place government censorship, or accuse users of crimes in the future based on redefining previously acceptable behavior — for example, creating a post on Facebook that criticizes a political candidate or their rhetoric. Before a change in law or authoritarian leadership, this could be an acceptable form of free speech, but afterwards it earns you the label of enemy of the state. Individual identification and anonymity are threatened due to the capacity to aggregate data about your every move online and profile you. Trying to create a new identity and separate yourself from this online profile is very difficult. Couple this with constant surveillance, and people’s freedom to do as they please is vastly diminished.

**Mass surveillance doesn’t work for its stated purpose.** “More than just being ineffective, the NSA’s surveillance efforts have actually made us less secure.” The Privacy and Civil Liberties Oversight Board found the “Section 215” program for bulk collection of telephone metadata to be nearly useless, as well as likely illegal and problematic in other ways. Aside from the inherent violations of privacy, Schneier condemns the NSA practice of stockpiling — instead of repairing — computer software vulnerabilities and government strong-arming of Internet firms to compel them to surrender customer data.

**Data is power — the structural core.** “Data is power. Any entity, whether public or private, that holds data about individuals has some ability to understand, predict, and manipulate their behavior.”

**Surveillance is a tactic of intimidation.** “Surveillance is a tactic of intimidation,” Schneier writes, and “in the US, we already see the beginnings of a chilling effect.” Surveillance shapes awareness and alters conduct. Many people will slow down when driving past a police car or a traffic surveillance camera. Almost all will modify their speech or their behavior depending on who is listening or watching.

**Solutions.** In the latter portions of the book, Schneier presents an action agenda for curbing inappropriate surveillance including steps that can be taken by government, by corporations, and by concerned members of the public. The proposals are principled and thoughtful, though he admits not all are readily achievable. The EU data protection framework is mentioned as a leading example of data protection regulation. Companies are called upon to fight government surveillance and support litigation efforts against warrants. Solutions for “the rest of us” are offered, both in the context of private lives (such as privacy-enhancing technologies or choosing the provider we trust most) as well as asking for political change (engaging with legislators, supporting relevant non-governmental organizations), and, most importantly, not giving up, because “fatalism is the enemy of change.”

Schneier acknowledged the paradox: “We need government regulations that protect our privacy by limiting what these sites can do with our data.” But as one commenter on his blog noted: “Calling for more government regulation when the government is a big part of the problem with ubiquitous surveillance seems counterproductive.” Another commenter put it more bluntly: “Does anyone seriously think that if a site that truly offered privacy gained any traction, that they wouldn’t be co-opted or shut down? The government has become far too addicted to the data to give it up. Changes to the law are unlikely to help, because, as with the ancient Chinese empire, changes at the top fail to change the system, which is enforced by an endless army of faceless bureaucrats.”

Schneier’s core objective was to preserve, or to restore, a domain of personal privacy that is impervious to unwanted intrusion or monitoring. He acknowledges the necessity of surveillance for valid law enforcement and intelligence purposes. “If we can provide law enforcement people with new ways to investigate crime, they’ll stop demanding that security be subverted for their benefit.”

Malcolm Gladwell stated: “The public conversation about surveillance in the digital age would be a good deal more intelligent if we all read Bruce Schneier first.”

The book was published in 2015. Every warning in it has been validated. The surveillance apparatus has expanded in every dimension Schneier identified. No comprehensive federal privacy law has been enacted. The corporate-government surveillance symbiosis has deepened. The data broker loophole remains open. The situation is categorically worse in every dimension he identified. *Data and Goliath* was an Occupy moment for cybersecurity — massive initial intellectual capital, perfect diagnosis, zero institutional capture. The book produced awareness without infrastructure.

### Rewiring Democracy (2025): The Attempted Transition from Diagnosis to Institutional Tooling

Schneier’s latest book, *Rewiring Democracy: How AI Will Transform Our Politics, Government, and Citizenship*, co-authored with Nathan Sanders and published by MIT Press on October 21, 2025, attempts to move from diagnosis to counter-strategy — what we might call the Claude Code equivalent of his intellectual project: an attempt to build durable integration into the systems where decisions are actually made.

The book examines how AI technologies will affect democracy in five broad areas: politics, legislating, administration, the judiciary, and citizenship. There is a lot to unpack, both positive and negative. Schneier noted: “We do talk about AI’s possible role in both democratic backsliding or restoring democracies, but the fundamental focus of the book is on present and future uses of AIs within functioning democracies. And, yes, we talk about AI-driven propaganda and artificial conversation. Some of what we write about is happening now, but much of what we write about is speculation.”

The book’s core thesis, described by *Nature* as resting on a “thorny premise,” is that democracy is an information system. AI is transforming that information system. Whether these outcomes enhance or degrade democracy depends on how we shape the development and use of AI technologies.

Schneier and Sanders describe how the sophistication of AI will fulfill demands from lawmakers for more complex legislation, reducing deference to the executive branch and altering the balance of power between lawmakers and administrators. They show how the scale and scope of AI is enhancing civil servants’ ability to shape private-sector behavior, automating either the enforcement or neglect of industry regulations. They explain how both lawyers and judges will leverage the speed of AI, upending how we think about law enforcement, litigation, and dispute resolution.

The optimistic case: AI can give legislators with limited resources help in drafting bills with fewer strings attached than a lobbyist or an advocacy organization’s model legislation. The first law anywhere known to have been written by AI arose from Porto Alegre, Brazil, when a city councillor simply needed some help writing a bill about water utility infrastructure and turned to ChatGPT. In the future, legislators might choose not just to use an AI model to draft the text of a bill but might actually choose to designate an AI model as the form of their legislation. Traditional textual legislation suffers from ambiguity and inflexibility when interpreted decades later. An AI model could clarify its intent with unlimited precision and express an interpretation of a rule in response to any future special case or scenario.

Powerful players in private industry and public life are already using AI to increase their influence, and AIs built by corporations to drive shareholder value aren’t designed to deliver the fairness and trust necessary to enhance democratic governance. But, steered in the right direction, the broad scope of an AI-augmented democracy would help citizens build consensus, express their voice, and organize against anti-democratic policies.

Schneier and Sanders lay out a four-part plan of action:

1. Resist inappropriate uses of AI.
1. Seek responsible uses of AI in governance.
1. Reform the ecosystem of AI.
1. Renovate our democracy to prepare it for AI.

Schneier himself acknowledges: “The last one feels most urgent right now.”

He states the power concentration problem directly: “We already know the answer, because we’ve seen it happen: in big tech in general and with social media in particular. The powerful get more powerful, and then use that power to enact legislative changes that further protect that power. The concentration of wealth and power is bigger than AI, of course. It’s bigger than technology. But it’s exacerbated by technologies like AI. Our task as a democracy is to ensure that technologies broadly distribute power amongst the many rather than concentrate it among the few. We return to this problem again and again in our book.”

He describes AI as “fundamentally a power magnifying technology. It takes the command of one person and executes on it with greater speed, scale, scope, and sophistication than any one human could.” That is exactly right. And the people who currently have AI — the consolidated state-corporate apparatus — are using it to magnify their power. The book’s proposed counter-uses require citizens to first obtain equivalent AI capabilities and institutional access — a bootstrapping problem with no clean entry point.

**The structural weakness.** The book was published on October 21, 2025. By that date, DOGE had already been operating for months, doing exactly what the book warned about in the abstract.

One Goodreads reviewer wrote: “Felt out of date as it predates 2025 governmental changes.” Another reviewer noted: “The real question that should have been asked throughout the book is whether our ‘democracy’ has benefited people and how artificial intelligence, either generative or agentic AI, can help fight bad actors or assist good actors in the system. Can AI be used by non-partisan groups to help educate voters? Should AI be used in the vote counting process? Should the population worry about governments using surveillance technology infused with AI?” That reviewer gave it a 6/10, identifying the core weakness: the book treats democracy as a functioning system that needs optimization, rather than a captured system that needs liberation.

Even Vint Cerf’s blurb contains the tell: “While Schneier and Sanders are more optimistic than I am about the future of artificial intelligence and policy, you will be glad to have taken the time to read and understand their well-articulated arguments.” When the man who helped build the internet is hedging against your optimism, that is a signal.

The book’s framework rests on a premise that maps directly onto the first-mover trap: it assumes the existence of institutional channels through which its recommendations can flow.

“Resist inappropriate uses of AI” — requires regulatory bodies with enforcement power. Those are being gutted.

“Seek responsible uses of AI in governance” — requires a government interested in responsible governance. DOGE is exfiltrating databases and handing them to Palantir.

“Reform the ecosystem of AI” — requires legislative action. The same Congress that didn’t mention Schneier’s testimony in their hearing summary.

“Renovate our democracy to prepare it for AI” — requires a functional democracy to renovate. Which circles back to the entire problem.

The book is proposing feature improvements to a platform that has been acquired by a hostile actor. It is writing a better user manual for a product whose new owner has already changed the terms of service.

### Congressional Testimony (June 2025): The Warning That Was Not Recorded

On June 5, 2025, Schneier testified before the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform at a hearing titled “The Federal Government in the Age of Artificial Intelligence.” He later wrote: “The other speakers mostly talked about how cool AI was — and sometimes about how cool their own company was — but I was asked by the Democrats to specifically talk about DOGE and the risks of exfiltrating our data from government agencies and feeding it into AIs.”

He outlined what he called a “DOGE approach” to data handling, with four distinct features:

**Data consolidation:** Exfiltrating and connecting massive U.S. databases to create a single pool of data covering all citizens.

**Reduced security protocols:** Removing access controls and audit logs, creating unmonitored copies of data, exposing highly sensitive data to cloud-based tools, seeking maximally permissive data access waivers, and eliminating previously required security protocols for vetting staff.

**AI training and processing:** Using AI tools to process data outside of carefully monitored environments.

**Offering data to private companies:** DOGE’s affiliates have spread across government. They are still exfiltrating massive US databases, processing them with AI and offering them to private companies such as Palantir.

He told Congress: “Data security breaches present significant dangers to everyone in the United States, from private citizens to corporations to government agencies to elected officials. Over the past four months, DOGE’s approach to data access has massively exacerbated the risk. DOGE employees have accessed and exfiltrated data from a variety of government agencies in order to, in part, train AI systems. Their actions have weakened security within the federal government by bypassing and disabling critical security measures, exporting sensitive data to environments with less security, and consolidating disparate data streams to create a massively attractive target for any adversary.”

He stated: “Data consolidation might seem harmless or even positive, but we have to understand what’s at stake when our data gets consolidated. Data is power. Any entity, whether public or private, that holds data about individuals has some ability to understand, predict, and manipulate their behavior.”

He warned: “Whether you fear government tyranny, attacks from foreign adversaries, or attacks from domestic malicious actors, the AI-fueled consolidation of citizen data should make your fears grow. If the consolidation is carried out recklessly and in secret, as DOGE affiliates are largely doing, this new and unchecked power presents serious risks to every American.”

He told Congress directly: “You all need to assume that adversaries have copies of all the data DOGE has exfiltrated and has established access into all the networks that DOGE has removed security controls from.”

He warned that any military action against the United States could be preceded by the zeroing-out of bank accounts for military and political leaders — made possible by the consolidation of Treasury and OPM data.

He warned that access to Americans’ data could give private companies “significant advantages in training AI systems and in setting business strategy. Without proper oversight, this access could lead to private companies profiting from sensitive information or foreign governments exploiting vulnerabilities. The safeguards protecting government data were built over years to protect Americans, but these protections are already eroding. The consequences could be immediate or unfold over time, leading to loss of services, harassment, discrimination, or manipulation by the government.”

In an earlier interview with the Harvard Kennedy School, Schneier was asked whether DOGE’s data handling could be secure. His response: “We know they’re not. Just the fact that it’s happening so quickly tells us so. Security is hard; it takes time, and nothing secure happens this quickly. I feel confident in saying there’s simply no way that they can be secure in what they’re doing. And that the insecurities are enormous. For example, I worry about the audit systems. We have comprehensive systems for recording what these systems do and what happens, and we use those audit records to go back and figure out what happened. If these audit systems have been compromised, and it’s likely they have, now an attacker can make undetectable changes in the system — and that is its own level of scariness.”

He added: “I think this actually could undermine the Trump administration’s agenda. Whatever this government actually wants to do, it almost certainly does not include giving foreign governments a full take of what agencies like the Treasury Department and OPM know and do.”

He noted: “In 2024, China hacked the Office of Personnel Management and took copies of some of that data. They wanted to be able to map who is involved in government, who has a clearance, and who might be a spy entering their own country.”

Representative Nancy Mace (R-SC), chairing the subcommittee, opened the hearing by focusing on AI’s potential as a productivity tool — “all the more necessary amid DOGE’s efforts to reduce the federal workforce.” She said: “The federal government has a responsibility to harness this technology to make government work faster and more efficiently for the American people.” Witnesses from think tanks and AI firms echoed the party line, talking up AI as a way to streamline inefficient bureaucracy and maintain economic competitiveness.

*The Register* reported that Schneier “played the skunk at the garden party.” Schneier’s message wasn’t what the lawmakers running the hearing wanted to hear — in fact, his testimony goes unmentioned amid the Oversight committee’s AI-boosting summary of the event.

He stated: “The previous four speakers have talked about the promises of this technology. I want to talk about the national security implications of the way our country is consolidating data and feeding it to AI models.”

