## V. The Safety Company and Its General Magic Arc

There is a company — dead since 2004, liquidated, its patents sold to Paul Allen — that illuminates Anthropic’s trajectory with the precision of a parable. It was called General Magic. The parallel is not cosmetic. It is structural, and the structural failures map onto Anthropic’s present with uncomfortable precision.

### General Magic: The Company That Invented the Future and Was Destroyed by It

General Magic was an American software and early smartphone electronics company co-founded by Bill Atkinson, Andy Hertzfeld, and Marc Porat. Based in Mountain View, California, the company developed precursors to USB, software modems, small touchscreens, touchscreen controller integrated circuits, ASICs, multimedia email, networked games, streaming TV, and early e-commerce notions. According to Electronics Weekly, the company “developed a precursor of USB, software modems, small touchscreens, touchscreen controller ICs, ASICs, multimedia email, networked games, streaming TV and early e-commerce notions.” According to former General Magic employee Marco DeMiroz, it was the “Fairchild of the 90s.”

The original project started in 1989 within Apple Computer, when Marc Porat convinced Apple’s then-CEO John Sculley that the next generation of computing would require a partnership of computer, communications, and consumer electronics companies to cooperate. Known as the Paradigm project, the project ran for some time within Apple, but management remained generally uninterested and the team struggled for resources. Eventually they approached Sculley with the idea of spinning off the group as a separate company, which occurred in May 1990. Apple took a minority stake, with Sculley joining the General Magic board.

Porat, Hertzfeld, and Atkinson were soon joined by Susan Kare, Joanna Hoffman (vice president of marketing), hardware pioneer Wendell Sander, Walt Broedner, and Megan Smith who joined from Apple Japan, and most of Apple’s System 7 team. The company initially operated in near-complete secrecy.

Marc Porat had conceptualized what was essentially an early version of the smartphone. The device, named Pocket Crystal, was a touchscreen mobile computer that could one day make calls, fax documents, play games, watch movies, and buy plane tickets. Marc Porat wrote in his notebook: “A small device that will be your phone, your wallet, and your window to the world.” In approximately 1994, Porat was filmed predicting “smart phones, smart pagers, and maybe even things like intelligent watches” — describing both the iPhone and Apple Watch decades ahead of time. Then a reporter asked him if it was possible that anyone would ever figure out a way to make any money from such products.

By 1992, some of the world’s largest electronics corporations, including Sony, Motorola, Matsushita, Philips, and AT&T Corporation were partners and investors in General Magic. Instead of manufacturing everything in-house, they assembled an unwieldy alliance of companies to make and maintain their product. Some of these companies were natural enemies — Sony and Panasonic, for instance, were deeply competitive in many markets. But they were supposed to work together. In reality, these companies and their inter-relationships brought enormous levels of complexity. As one team member described it: “We were putting sixteen of the largest companies on the planet, who are natural enemies, into the same room at the same time. We knew we were innovating. No one had done anything like that. And if it succeeded, it would change everything.”

The company went public in 1995 — with no shipped product or revenue — at a value of $834 million, raising over $90 million. It was a unicorn before there was such a thing.

The company’s main product was Magic Cap, an operating system which allowed users to “set their own rules for message alerts and acquiring information” on PDAs. The basic idea was to distribute the typical computing load across many machines in the network. The company also introduced the programming language Telescript, compiled into cross-platform bytecode in much the same fashion as Java, but able to migrate running processes between virtual machines. The developers saw a time when Telescript application engines would be ubiquitous, and interconnected Telescript engines would form a “Telescript Cloud” across which mobile applications could execute.

The company achieved many technical breakthroughs: software modems (eliminating the need for modem chips), small touchscreens and touchscreen controller ASICs, highly integrated systems-on-a-chip designs, rich multimedia email, networked games, streaming television, and early versions of e-commerce. It offered futuristic features like a touchscreen, downloadable apps, and animated emojis — the first of its kind.

Then came the collapse.

In 1992-1993, while Sculley was still a director of General Magic, Apple entered the consumer electronics market with a poorly received personal digital assistant that became the Apple Newton. Sculley launched the Newton at the 1993 Consumer Electronics Show, and General Magic’s staff were blindsided. For the past few years, General Magic had been developing their product in “stealth mode.” All work documents were shredded and thrown in separate bins. Employees were told not to discuss work matters outside the office. The company believed that if their concept leaked, they would lose their competitive edge. One exception was Apple’s Sculley, who had some access — General Magic had been spun out of Apple, after all; Sculley was on its board.

Andy Hertzfeld said, later: “They were our closest partner, who really gave us our life. And so when we found out they were trying to kill us, we felt completely betrayed.”

When General Magic finally shipped in 1994 — under the threat of Apple’s Newton — they hadn’t made the Pocket Crystal that Porat first dreamed of in 1989. Instead, they released the Sony Magic Link. It weighed 1.5 lbs and was priced at $800 (approximately $1,560 in 2022 dollars). It was slow because the processors of the time couldn’t keep up, and the battery disappeared in the blink of an eye.

Tony Fadell, who worked at General Magic, thought it would be revolutionary — people could now carry a personal computer with them wherever they went. But nobody bought it. In the end only three to four thousand Magic Link devices were sold, and mostly to family and friends. Fadell said that it crushed him.

The biggest mistake was ignoring the open Internet. General Magic was building its own closed network while the rest of the world was just beginning to dive into the World Wide Web. They were building the world’s most beautiful swimming pool while an ocean was flowing right next to them.

By 1997, the company’s original idea was dead. It officially shut down in 2002. Paul Allen purchased most of its patents in 2004.

The people involved at the time were devastated. But many General Magic employees went on to bigger and better things:

- Tony Fadell went to Apple, where he created the iPod and then the iPhone — using every painful lesson learned from General Magic.
- Andy Rubin created the Android system, which now powers billions of phones.
- Pierre Omidyar wrote the code for his little side project while sitting in the General Magic office — that project is today’s eBay.
- Megan Smith became a VP for Google, then the third CTO of the US under President Obama.
- Kevin Lynch helped invent the Apple Watch.

None of them got rich off their General Magic work, but they can all take pride in knowing they created something that was far ahead of its time. The engineers of General Magic didn’t lose. They simply drew the map that we all use today.

The lessons Silicon Valley learned thanks to failures like General Magic helped create our digital revolution. The story of General Magic is a reminder that in technology, timing is more important than the idea itself. You can be right, you can be a genius, but if you show up to the party three hours too early, you’ll be sitting in an empty room by yourself.

So much of Apple’s current DNA shows up in General Magic. The focus on the user, obsession with design, insistence on simplicity, and love of big ideas is already there. A new documentary about the small company that was decades ahead of its time, the film *General Magic*, opened at the Tribeca Film Festival on April 20, 2018, and raises questions about Silicon Valley’s philosophy on failure.

### The Parallel with Anthropic: Point by Point

The parallels between General Magic and Anthropic are structural, not cosmetic:

**Origin story.** General Magic was founded by the people who built the Macintosh — the most important team at the most important company in personal computing — who left because they believed the parent organization couldn’t see what was coming. Anthropic was founded in 2021 by former OpenAI researchers, including co-founders Dario and Daniela Amodei, who left because they believed OpenAI couldn’t maintain safety principles at scale. Both companies were born from disillusionment with the organization that should have led the revolution.

**The parent betrayal.** Apple’s John Sculley — who was on General Magic’s board and had access to its proprietary work — launched the Newton at CES 1993, blindsiding the team. Hertzfeld: “They were our closest partner, who really gave us our life. And so when we found out they were trying to kill us, we felt completely betrayed.” Anthropic’s parent — OpenAI, the organization its founders built — has become its primary competitor, systematically abandoning the safety principles that motivated Anthropic’s founding while publicly claiming safety leadership. Sam Altman hasn’t just launched a Newton. He has launched a $20+ billion consumer juggernaut with Microsoft’s distribution network behind it, while publicly claiming safety leadership. The parent didn’t just compete — it adopted the language of the child’s mission while gutting its substance.

From 2024 to 2025, OpenAI experienced a systematic exodus of senior executives. Co-founder and Chief Scientist Ilya Sutskever left to found Safe Superintelligence. CTO Mira Murati left to found Thinking Machines Lab. Co-founders John Schulman and Jan Leike, head of the Superalignment team, went to Anthropic. Chief Research Officer Bob McGrew left. Vice President of Research Barret Zoph left. Co-founder and president Greg Brockman went on extended leave. Of OpenAI’s original 11 co-founders, only Sam Altman and researcher Wojciech Zaremba remained full-time by the end of 2025. A former employee told Fortune: “OpenAI without Ilya is a different company; OpenAI without Greg is a very different company.”

Anthropic presents a different picture. All seven co-founders — Dario Amodei, Daniela Amodei, Jared Kaplan, Jack Clark, Sam McCandlish, Ben Mann, and Tom Brown — are still with the company, and there has not been a single public executive-level departure in its five-year history. The contrast is so striking that it’s worth asking what Anthropic did to keep people around. In early 2026, Forbes estimated that each of the seven co-founders held approximately 1.8% of the shares, with minimal variation. At a $380 billion valuation, each person’s stake was worth about $6.8 billion. This nearly equal equity structure differs sharply from Silicon Valley norms, where the CEO typically holds the largest share.

**The alliance problem.** General Magic assembled an unwieldy alliance — AT&T, Apple, Motorola, Sony, Panasonic, Phillips — some natural enemies, all supposed to work together, all bringing enormous complexity. Anthropic operates its models on a broad hardware base, including AWS Trainium, Google TPUs, and NVIDIA GPUs. Amazon remains the primary cloud provider and training partner. Claude is the only frontier AI model available on all three major cloud platforms: Amazon Web Services (Bedrock), Google Cloud (Vertex AI), and Microsoft Azure (Foundry). But Amazon has its own Titan models. Google has Gemini. Microsoft backs OpenAI. The alliance partners are simultaneously investors, cloud providers, and competitors with their own AI ambitions.

**The infrastructure mismatch.** General Magic built a luxury Ferrari, but the world didn’t have asphalt yet. The infrastructure — broadband, processors, batteries — didn’t exist to support the vision. The Sony Magic Link cost $800, was slow, and the battery died. Anthropic faces the inverse mismatch: the infrastructure for surveillance exists and is operational. The institutional capture that prevents the regulatory infrastructure for safety is already in place. The question is not whether the world is ready for responsible AI. It is whether responsible AI can survive in a world that has been architecturally designed to prevent it.

Anthropic’s inference costs were 23% higher than anticipated. Gross margins improved from -94% in 2024 to approximately 40% in 2025 — still 10 percentage points below earlier optimistic expectations. The lower-than-expected gross profit margin resulted from the costs of running Anthropic models for paying customers on servers from Google and Amazon. If Anthropic also counted inference costs for Claude chatbot users that don’t pay for a subscription, its gross margin would be about 38%. In contrast, OpenAI projected a gross margin of around 46% in 2025. Both companies spend a tremendous amount on renting servers to develop new models — training costs, which don’t factor into gross margins — making it more difficult to turn a net profit than it is for traditional software and cloud firms. Anthropic expected its training costs for 2025 to be roughly $4.1 billion. OpenAI expected to spend $9.4 billion on compute for training.

**The timing problem.** General Magic arrived too early — the market didn’t exist yet. Anthropic’s safety mission faces the inverse timing problem. The market exists — $30 billion in revenue proves it. But the market exists for AI, not for safe AI. Safety is the feature that enterprise customers pay a premium for today because regulation is uncertain and liability exposure is unclear. The moment regulatory clarity arrives — in either direction — that premium evaporates. If regulations tighten, every AI company will claim safety. If regulations loosen (the Powell trajectory), safety becomes a drag on capability and price.

### Anthropic’s Current Numbers — The Full Picture

As of April 2026, Anthropic has overtaken OpenAI in annualized revenue — a remarkable shift:

Anthropic’s annualized recurring revenue trajectory: $1 billion in January 2025, $5 billion by August 2025, $9 billion by year-end 2025, $14 billion in February 2026, $19 billion in March 2026, surpassing $30 billion in early April 2026. OpenAI in the same period: approximately $13 billion in 2025, approximately $24-25 billion by April 2026 ($2 billion per month).

Anthropic grew 30 times in 15 months, going from an order of magnitude behind OpenAI to surpassing it by 20%. OpenAI’s own growth has been substantial, but compared to Anthropic’s, it is a contrast between steady growth and explosive acceleration. Anthropic has been called the fastest-growing company in history based on this trajectory.

The decisive difference lies in strategic focus: Anthropic consistently targets the enterprise business, while OpenAI has traditionally aimed at end consumers with ChatGPT.

Claude Code was the catalyst. Launched in May 2025, the specialized coding assistant reached $1 billion in run-rate revenue within six months. This represents approximately 20% of Anthropic’s total revenue from a single product vertical. Claude Code now holds 54% of the enterprise coding market, compared to OpenAI’s 21%. Something built by four engineers in ten days had most of its code written by Claude Code itself.

In January 2026, Anthropic released Cowork, extending the same concept from developers to all white-collar roles. Since Cowork’s launch, approximately $2 trillion in market value has been erased from the global SaaS sector.

Enterprise adoption specifics: Anthropic commands 40% of enterprise LLM spending, surpassing OpenAI’s 27% and Google’s 21%, with 85% of revenue from business customers. Over 1,000 enterprise customers spend more than $1 million annually — doubling in just two months. Eight of the Fortune 10 are clients. Ramp’s enterprise spending data shows Anthropic’s share of corporate AI expenditures surged from 10% at the beginning of 2025 to over 65% by February 2026. Seven out of every ten new customers choose Anthropic.

In the enterprise LLM API market, Anthropic’s Claude 3.5 Sonnet captures 32% of the market, compared to OpenAI’s GPT-4o at 25%. Anthropic’s enterprise market share grew from 18% to 29% in 2025. Business customers account for 80% of revenue. In contrast, OpenAI’s enterprise revenue represents only 40% of its overall income.

Consumer share remains dwarfed by ChatGPT (68% market share, approximately 900 million weekly active users) and Google Gemini (18.2%). Claude had approximately 19 million consumer users by Q3 2025. Anthropic treats consumer products as enterprise lead generation rather than primary revenue drivers.

Funding: Anthropic has raised approximately $64 billion in total funding. Its February 2026 Series G brought in $30 billion at a $380 billion post-money valuation, led by GIC and Coatue, with co-leads including D.E. Shaw Ventures, Dragoneer, Founders Fund, ICONIQ, and MGX. Strategic investors Amazon and Google have made massive commitments, with Amazon alone investing up to $8 billion.

Infrastructure: Anthropic has concluded a far-reaching infrastructure agreement with Google and Broadcom covering several gigawatts of next-generation computing capacity. The new TPU capacities are set to come online incrementally from 2027 onward and will be located predominantly in the United States. This is an extension of the commitment announced in November 2025 to invest $50 billion in American AI infrastructure. Anthropic recently agreed to purchase $21 billion of Google’s tensor processing units to gain more control over the hardware it uses so it can reduce computing costs.

Profitability path: Unlike OpenAI, Anthropic projects positive free cash flow by 2027 with potential $17 billion in cash flow by 2028. Anthropic has previously projected gross margins above 70% by 2027. OpenAI has projected gross margins of at least 70% by 2029. OpenAI forecasts losses exceeding $14 billion in 2026.

IPO: Anthropic is evaluating an initial public offering as early as October 2026, which could raise over $60 billion, with its valuation reaching $380 billion.

The shadows: High revenue does not equate to profitability. Exorbitant computing costs mean that AI inference costs are high, and with free users making up 95% of the user base, compute-intensive products have become a profit black hole. While gross margin improved significantly from -94% in 2024, it is expected to be around 40% in 2025 — still 10 percentage points below previous targets. Legal battles with the government: refusing the Pentagon’s request to modify safety restrictions led to being labeled a “supply chain risk.” Although the court temporarily ruled the government exceeded its authority, the trouble is far from over.

### The Fork: Path A, Path B, and Why Path C Does Not Exist

Anthropic faces a binary that maps onto every pattern traced in this chapter:

**Path A: Maintain safety principles.** The Pentagon labels you a supply chain risk. Government contracts go to competitors. Regulated industries follow the government’s lead. Your $30 billion revenue becomes a ceiling, not a floor. You become the Volvo of AI — respected, safe, niche. A security tools company at best, or irrelevant.

**Path B: Compromise safety principles to maintain growth.** You win the Pentagon contracts. You become the full-stack AI infrastructure layer for government and enterprise. Revenue hits $70 billion by 2028 as projected. But now you are Palantir with better PR. The safety research becomes the intellectual veneer on a surveillance-compatible platform. You have won the market and lost the mission.

There is no Path C where you maintain pure safety principles and dominate the market and resist government pressure to weaponize your products. The institutional architecture that Powell built does not allow for that path. The regulatory capture, the legal framework that says corporations can’t dictate how government uses “lawfully acquired” technology, the absence of federal privacy law — all of that forecloses the possibility of a company being both dominant and principled at scale.

The safety positioning is Anthropic’s brand differentiator, but brand is not the same as market structure. If Claude Code is the distribution mechanism that keeps Anthropic competitive, then Anthropic’s survival depends on developer adoption, which depends on capability parity with OpenAI and Google, which creates the exact same incentive gradient that every other AI company faces: ship faster, restrict less, expand use cases. The safety research becomes the thing you fund with the revenue from the thing that undermines the safety research.

The RLHF alignment work, the constitutional AI papers, the responsible scaling policy — these are intellectually serious. But they exist inside a company that needs to grow revenue in a market where the competitors have fewer scruples and deeper pockets. Microsoft backs OpenAI with functionally unlimited capital and enterprise distribution through Azure, Office, and GitHub Copilot. Google has Gemini embedded across Search, Workspace, and Android — billions of existing touchpoints.

The market does not reward being right about safety. It rewards distribution. Schneier has been right about surveillance for twenty years and his congressional testimony got omitted from the committee summary. Anthropic can be right about alignment for twenty years and still lose to whoever ships the better coding assistant with fewer guardrails.

The deeper structural point: the entities doing the most thoughtful work on the risks — Schneier, Anthropic, the grassroots think tanks, the EFF — are all operating inside market and institutional structures that systematically punish the very caution they are advocating. Safety is a cost center in a growth market. Restraint is a competitive disadvantage in an arms race. And the Powell-descended institutional architecture ensures that the regulatory bodies that could turn safety into a market requirement are either captured, defunded, or ignored.

Anthropic saying it won’t allow its technology to be used for mass surveillance while the Pentagon says a private company can’t dictate how the government uses lawfully acquired technology — that is the entire power asymmetry in one exchange. The company with the principles has less power than the institution without them. That is not a safety strategy. That is a negotiating position, and not a strong one.

To compete, Anthropic has to go the Microsoft way — compete in hardware and model compression, be a leader in AI, not just safe AI — because AI is. It is too late for the distinction to hold. The $30 billion in revenue and the infrastructure agreements with Google and Broadcom show they are already doing this — locking in hardware, vertically integrating compute, competing on infrastructure rather than just safety principles. They have become an enterprise platform company. Not a safety research lab. An enterprise platform company with safety research, which is a very different thing.

### The Projection Timeline

**2026-2027: The golden window.** Enterprise revenue compounds. Claude Code dominates. The safety brand is a genuine competitive advantage in regulated industries. IPO happens. Valuation is stratospheric. Everything looks like vindication.

**2027-2028: The infrastructure squeeze.** Both companies project gross margins above 70% by 2027-2029, which would put them closer to publicly traded software firms. If those margins don’t materialize — and the cost structure of responsible AI makes them harder to hit — the public market will punish the stock. Investors don’t care about alignment research when margins compress.

**2028-2030: The Pentagon fork.** The government pressure doesn’t go away. It intensifies as AI becomes more central to military and intelligence operations. The legal battles with the government over safety restrictions are far from over. Anthropic either capitulates on defense applications or watches competitors absorb those contracts and the revenue they generate.

**The long tail.** If Anthropic maintains its principles and loses the government and defense market, it becomes a security tools company — high-integrity, respected, niche. Profitable, maybe, but not the world-shaping force its founders intended. The safety research continues. Papers get published. The alignment problem gets better understood. And the actual deployment of AI at civilizational scale happens inside companies that absorbed Anthropic’s talent and ideas without its constraints.

Just like General Magic. The company died. The vision lived. But it lived inside Apple, Google, and eBay — not inside the company that held the original vision.

**The cruelest version of this future:** Anthropic’s safety research becomes the intellectual foundation for whatever “responsible AI framework” the captured regulatory state eventually mandates — a framework written by the think tanks Powell’s infrastructure built, enforced by the agencies those think tanks staffed, and designed to protect incumbents while wearing the language of Anthropic’s mission like a skin suit.

The $30 billion in revenue buys them time. It does not change the underlying dynamics. AI safety as a competitive differentiator works exactly until the moment it conflicts with a customer’s operational requirements — and when your customer is the U.S. Department of Defense, that moment arrives with the force of the state behind it.

