## VII. The Sovereign Algorithm’s Contractor

If the Powell Memo built the institutional architecture of capture, and the data broker loophole built the commercial infrastructure of surveillance, and Schneier diagnosed the crisis with precision that the system was structurally designed to ignore, and Anthropic attempted to build a responsible alternative inside a market that punishes responsibility, and the democratic counter-movements remain trapped in the first-mover cycle of activation without institutional capture — then Palantir Technologies is the entity that fused all of these threads into a single operational system at the heart of the state.

Palantir was co-founded in 2003 by Peter Thiel — a venture capitalist, PayPal co-founder, early Facebook investor, and one of the most consequential political donors of the twenty-first century — with early funding from In-Q-Tel, the CIA’s venture capital arm. The company’s software — Gotham for intelligence and defense, Foundry for commercial and government operations — integrates disparate data streams into unified analytical platforms. Its original purpose was counterterrorism. Its current purpose is everything.

### The Numbers

In 2025, Palantir’s federal contracts nearly doubled, rising to $970.5 million. Multi-year contract ceilings awarded in 2025 alone total over $13.7 billion. That is $84.26 per taxpayer if fully exercised. Revenue has grown 6.5 times in six years. After decelerating to 17% growth in 2023, growth re-accelerated dramatically in 2024-2025, coinciding with massive new federal contract awards. FY2025 revenue hit $4.48 billion — up 56% in a single year. The company crossed $1 billion in quarterly revenue for the first time in the second quarter. Twenty-two years after its founding, Palantir’s software runs inside the CIA, the Pentagon, ICE, the IRS, the CDC, the Army, and dozens of other agencies.

Palantir is a data analytics company and defense contractor that sells surveillance technology to the US government and allied countries, as well as to the private sector. It has won $1.9 billion in US contracts since 2008. CEO Alex Karp received $6.8 billion in compensation in 2024, making him the highest-paid public company CEO that year.

OpenAI, founded in 2015, is valued at roughly $852 billion after its early-2026 fundraise. Anthropic, founded in 2021, is valued at $380 billion after its February 2026 Series G. Palantir operates in a different category — not a foundation model company but the integration layer, the company that takes data from everywhere and makes it operationally useful for the state. It is the connective tissue between the data broker ecosystem and government power.

### The Contracts: The Operational Architecture of the Sovereign Algorithm

**U.S. Army — $10 billion over a decade.** The largest single award. This multi-year contract makes Palantir the backbone data platform for the U.S. Army’s modernization strategy, integrating their Foundry, TITAN, and Vantage products across Army operations. What it does: aggregates sensor data, logistics, personnel readiness, and intelligence into a single operational picture. Why it matters: this is a generational lock-in. Once the Army’s data infrastructure runs on Palantir, switching costs become effectively infinite. The agreement creates a “comprehensive framework for the Army’s future software and data needs” that provides the government with purchasing flexibility and removes contract-related fees and procurement timelines. It consolidates 75 total contracts into one enterprise deal.

**Project Maven — evolved from experiment to permanent infrastructure.** Project Maven began in 2017 as a Pentagon effort to use AI to help analysts process massive volumes of surveillance imagery and video, but it has since evolved into a broader military intelligence and targeting platform that fuses data from multiple sensors to identify objects, assess threats, and support operational decisions. The Department of Defense is expanding its use of AI by formalizing Palantir’s Maven system as a long-term program, signaling a shift from experimental tools to operational infrastructure.

Palantir’s work on Maven has expanded through multiple awards: a five-year, $480 million Army contract in 2024, a roughly $100 million follow-on expansion later that year, and a 2025 contract modification valued at up to $795 million for continued system support and software licensing. The latest move does not replace those contracts. Instead, it builds on earlier efforts by expanding Maven from a narrower intelligence program into a broader, Pentagon-backed capability intended for long-term, department-wide use.

**ICE — ImmigrationOS.** A $30 million no-bid contract to build an “Immigration Lifecycle Operating System,” referred to as ImmigrationOS, to track self-deportations, help select targets for arrests, and create an “Immigration Lifecycle Process” to increase the efficiency of deportations. Palantir has been a contractor for ICE since 2011, but this contract — awarded in April 2025 — represents a qualitative shift: an AI platform that identifies noncitizens and tracks deportations. Palantir’s work with ICE comes as President Trump has worked to make good on his promise to carry out the largest mass deportation operation in history.

This is the system that processes human beings into the categories that determine whether they are inside or outside — the algorithmic sovereign decision applied to immigration enforcement. This is, in the language of “Jus Algoritmi,” the production of homo sacer by algorithmic means.

**IRS — unified API layer.** Palantir employees were embedded at the IRS alongside DOGE (Department of Government Efficiency) staff to build a “mega API” at the IRS that could access data from across the agency. The tech outlet Wired separately reported on this effort. In September 2025, the Treasury Department announced that it had awarded a contract to Palantir to create a “unified API layer” — formalizing what had begun as an ad hoc DOGE-driven project.

What it does: creates a single access point to all taxpayer data — Social Security numbers, tax returns, employment records, bank information, and filing history. What they access: every tax return filed in the United States.

Why it matters: multiple members of Congress allege this violates Internal Revenue Code Sections 6103 and 7213A — post-Watergate laws specifically enacted to prevent the weaponization of taxpayer data. Senator Ron Wyden, Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, Senator Elizabeth Warren, and Senator Edward Markey have formally demanded answers from Palantir CEO Alex Karp.

Wyden said he’s still not convinced Palantir is a trusted contractor. “Palantir is one of the companies making a lot of money out of this,” he told The Hill. “There are privacy problems with what they’re doing. I mean, this has been a great, as I call it, a great harvest for these kind of technology operations and virtually no accountability.”

One former agency official said it wasn’t surprising to see the increased use of Palantir at ICE, given its capabilities and the administration’s relationships with the company. DOGE wanted to use the company’s Foundry tool to deal with legacy technology challenges that had existed for decades. The IRS had already been using Palantir for several years for fraud detection work and work done under the Office of Criminal Investigations. While the agency had been focused on lessening its dependence on antiquated programming languages like COBOL, DOGE was highly interested in improving the agency’s approach to the “data layer.” While there were certainly concerns about vendor lock-in, other companies are also trying to make government agencies more dependent on their software.

The interest in Palantir stemmed from the Trump administration’s more aggressive posture.

**Israel — targeting databases.** After announcing a “strategic partnership” with Israel in January 2024, Palantir’s involvement in Gaza and the occupied West Bank expanded considerably. Using a mix of intercepted communications, satellite material, and other digital data sources, Palantir began integrating these inputs to help produce targeting databases — effectively, “kill lists” — for the Israeli military. It has also cultivated close ties with US security agencies, particularly during the Trump administration, and has worked with Israel in its occupation of the West Bank and what critics describe as genocide in Gaza.

The company drew heavily on the expertise of former members of Israel’s cyber-intelligence unit, 8200.

According to Amnesty International: “Palantir has a track record of flagrantly disregarding international law and standards, both in the violations of the human rights of migrants in the United States, to which it risks contributing to, and its ongoing supply of artificial intelligence (AI) products and services to the Israeli military and intelligence services that are linked to Israel’s ongoing genocide in Gaza.”

Activists have organized protests against the company’s work for the Israeli military, as well as its developing role at U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement.

**DOD as primary revenue source.** DOD alone accounts for the majority of Palantir’s government revenue. The company’s federal portfolio has mushroomed under the Trump administration’s second term, but it is also facing growing scrutiny over its work with the administration.

### The Connection to Schneier’s DOGE Testimony

Bruce Schneier’s June 2025 testimony before the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform identified the final piece of this architecture. He stated that DOGE’s affiliates have spread across government, that they are “still exfiltrating massive US databases, processing them with AI and offering them to private companies such as Palantir.”

Access to Americans’ data could give private companies significant advantages in training AI systems and in setting business strategy. Without proper oversight, this access could lead to private companies profiting from sensitive information or foreign governments exploiting vulnerabilities.

What Palantir represents in the architecture of capture is the final integration: the point at which corporate infrastructure, state power, and algorithmic sovereignty become indistinguishable. The data brokers harvest the raw material. DOGE consolidates it from inside the government. Palantir refines it into operational platforms. The state consumes it. And the citizen whose data flows through this pipeline has no standing, no visibility into the process, and no meaningful mechanism of appeal.

The sovereign algorithm does not merely advise the state. It becomes the state’s operating system. And the company that built it answers to its shareholders, not to the demos.

