## VIII. The Manifesto: From Powell’s Confidential Memo to Palantir’s Public Declaration

On April 20, 2026, Palantir posted a 22-point summary of *The Technological Republic: Hard Power, Soft Belief, and the Future of the West* — co-authored by CEO Alex Karp and head of corporate affairs Nicholas Zamiska — to its X account. The post accumulated over 32 million views.

*The Technological Republic* is a #1 New York Times bestseller. NPR named it a staff top pick for 2025. Barnes & Noble listed it among the best business books of the year. George Will wrote in *The Washington Post*: “Not since Allan Bloom’s astonishingly successful 1987 book *The Closing of the American Mind* — more than one million copies sold — has there been a cultural critique as sweeping as Karp’s.” Niall Ferguson called it “a stirring manifesto for a new Manhattan Project for the AI Age.” The *Wall Street Journal* called it “ambitious, dense, cultured… nuanced, caveated, largely compelling, and reassuringly humble.” *Wired* called it “a surprisingly readable polemic that skewers Silicon Valley for insufficient patriotism.” The *Washington Post* described it as “as clear and bracing as reveille.” The *Times of London* called it “the AI manifesto inspiring Keir Starmer’s government.” The *New York Times Magazine* noted that it “argues for a return to the values of the early Cold War, when technology, culture and national defense were united in common purpose.”

The book is billed as “a passionate call for the West to wake up to our new reality” and promises to “lift the veil on Palantir and its broader political project from the inside.”

### The 22 Points

The manifesto’s core arguments, as posted to X:

1. “Silicon Valley owes a moral debt to the country that made its rise possible. The engineering elite of Silicon Valley has an affirmative obligation to participate in the defense of the nation.”
1. “We must rebel against the tyranny of the apps. Is the iPhone our greatest creative if not crowning achievement as a civilization? The object has changed our lives, but it may also now be limiting and constraining our sense of the possible.”
1. “Free email is not enough. The decadence of a culture or civilization, and indeed its ruling class, will be forgiven only if that culture is capable of delivering economic growth and security for the public.”
1. “The limits of soft power, of soaring rhetoric alone, have been exposed. The ability of free and democratic societies to prevail requires something more than moral appeal. It requires hard power, and hard power in this century will be built on software.”
1. “The question is not whether A.I. weapons will be built; it is who will build them and for what purpose. Our adversaries will not pause to indulge in theatrical debates about the merits of developing technologies with critical military and national security applications. They will proceed.”
1. “National service should be a universal duty. We should, as a society, seriously consider moving away from an all-volunteer force and only fight the next war if everyone shares in the risk and the cost.”
1. “If a U.S. Marine asks for a better rifle, we should build it; and the same goes for software.”

The manifesto asserts that “not all cultures are equal. Some have proved middling, and worse, regressive and harmful.” It calls for the U.S. to renew a shared culture for the “country’s continued survival and cohesion,” arguing that “the old means of manufacturing a nation, the civic rituals of an educational system, mandatory service in national defense, religion, a shared language, and a thriving and free press have all but been dismantled or withered from neglect and abuse.”

In a 2025 NYT DealBook Summit interview titled on YouTube “Alex Karp Reveals Why Palantir Is the Most Dangerous Company on Earth,” Karp stated: “No one would listen to the superiority of our ideas if our ability to organize in violence was inferior… Every single person in the world believes this outside of the faculty of Harvard. And certainly our adversaries know to be true.” He argued that the rule of law and meritocracy are only possible when backed by military superiority, which in this century is built on AI and software.

He explained his priorities: “I care about two issues: I care about immigration and reestablishing the deterrent capacity of America… On those two issues, this president [Trump] has performed.”

He has explicitly stated he is “proud” of supporting Israel’s war efforts and acknowledged a “strategic partnership” with Israel’s Ministry of Defense for “war-related missions” since early 2024.

He shared how being “massively dyslexic” shaped his leadership style: “If you are massively dyslexic, you cannot play a playbook… we learn to think freely… I process in a way that has very little to do with what anyone else thinks.”

### The Critical Response

Al Jazeera described the manifesto as “an AI-driven threat to humanity’s existence” and “technofascism,” noting that “the publication of what appears to be a 22-point manifesto comes at a critical time for Palantir, which faces global criticism for its support of US President Donald Trump’s controversial immigration crackdown and its backing of the Israeli military’s actions in Gaza and the occupied West Bank.”

*The Nation* called it “a self-serving broadside steeped in oligarchic hubris and authoritarian nihilism.” The review continued: “Under his dystopian vision, Palantir would thrive and grow because safety and security are conflated with hard power — i.e., technological and military shows of force. Basic norms of international relations will be discarded entirely — a process now sent into overdrive by the Trump White House.” And: “He has never experienced the horrors of war firsthand. Like many Silicon Valley billionaires, he travels with a personal security force that ensures his personal safety at every level — but he’s happy to endanger the lives of others if it justifies spending more money on Palantir’s burgeoning defense portfolio. Like any other war profiteer, Karp will simply keep padding his bottom line, and will never be compelled by law to fight and die in a needless war because a billionaire wanted to make more money.”

Dave Karpf, associate professor at George Washington University’s School of Media & Public Affairs, wrote in TechPolicy.Press: “There is nothing in this ‘America First’-sounding manifesto that wouldn’t fit comfortably within a modern-day Mussolini regime.” He added: “It takes a certain audacity to survey the US landscape in 2026 and assert that ‘elites’ are intolerant to religious belief. Christian Nationalists have taken over much of the government. Likewise, the rejection of pluralism and the smug assertion that some cultures are good and others are middling, regressive, and harmful is shockingly regressive.” He noted that when he read the book, “my reaction was, ‘this book should have been a tweet.’ It now seems Palantir agrees.” He described the manifesto as “as subtle as a MAGA hat” and concluded: “Time and again, Karp exhibits the moral compass and complexity of a Bond villain.”

Engadget described it as reading “like the ramblings of a comic book villain.”

*Fortune* noted that “the point that drew the most scrutiny was the authors’ claim that some cultures have proved ‘middling, and worse, regressive and harmful,’” particularly given that Palantir provides technology to ICE and recently built ImmigrationOS.

One analysis framed the manifesto within the concept of “techno-sovereignty” — noting that “Alex Karp isn’t just selling software; he is selling a worldview. In his manifesto, Karp argues that the West’s ‘peace-time’ mindset is a liability. By framing the integration of software into the ‘kill chain’ of national defense as a moral obligation for the engineering elite, he is shifting Western defense policy priorities.”

### The Through-Line: Powell to Karp

Read the Powell Memo and *The Technological Republic* side by side. The through-line is direct:

Powell, 1971: American business is under attack. The engineering of political power — through universities, media, courts, and legislatures — is a moral obligation of the corporate class. The regulatory state must be weakened. Corporate interests must capture the institutions of democratic governance. Political power must be assiduously cultivated. Television and textbooks must be kept under constant surveillance. The judiciary is perhaps the most important instrument for social, economic, and political change.

Karp, 2025: Silicon Valley has failed its moral obligation to the nation. Hard power must be built on software. AI weapons must be built by American companies. The limits of soft power have been exposed. Technology companies must participate in defense. National service should be universal. Some cultures are regressive and harmful. No one would listen to the superiority of our ideas if our ability to organize in violence was inferior.

Powell called for corporate capture of democratic institutions to protect free enterprise. Karp calls for the fusion of Silicon Valley and the military-intelligence apparatus to project hard power. Powell wanted to monitor textbooks. Karp builds the systems that monitor populations. Powell wanted to shape the judiciary. Karp builds the platforms that the judiciary cannot yet govern. Powell’s project created the regulatory vacuum. Karp’s company fills it — with software that tracks immigrants, consolidates taxpayer data, identifies bombing targets, and processes the raw material of democratic citizenship through algorithms that no elected body controls and no affected person can appeal.

The Powell Memo was a confidential strategy document for the Chamber of Commerce. *The Technological Republic* is a New York Times bestseller posted as a 22-point manifesto on a platform with 32 million views. The quiet part is now the loud part. The institutional capture is so complete that the beneficiaries no longer need to conceal the architecture. They can publish it, promote it, receive praise from George Will and Niall Ferguson, and profit from it — while the company simultaneously operates ImmigrationOS for ICE, embeds employees in the IRS alongside DOGE staff, holds a $10 billion Army contract, produces targeting databases for the Israeli military, and processes the data that Schneier warned Congress had almost certainly already been compromised by foreign adversaries.

The architecture is no longer hidden. Its architects are posting the blueprints on social media and selling them at Barnes & Noble. The machine that ate democracy is publishing its own user manual.

